  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What does fondant taste like? How is it made?",
  "response": "Fondant is a type of icing that has a smooth, pliable texture and is often used to cover cakes and create decorative elements. Its taste can be described as sweet and sugary, somewhat similar to marshmallows, though it can also have a slightly chewy texture depending on how it is prepared and used. Some people find it overly sweet, especially when used in large quantities.\n\n### How Fondant is Made:\n\nThere are two main types of fondant: **rolled fondant** and **poured fondant**.\n\n#### Rolled Fondant:\n1. **Ingredients**:\n   - Powdered sugar (confectioners' sugar)\n   - Corn syrup\n   - Gelatin or marshmallows (for stability)\n   - Water\n   - Flavoring (optional)\n   - Glycerin (optional for smoothness)\n   \n2. **Preparation**:\n   - If using gelatin, dissolve it in water and let it bloom. \n   - Mix the corn syrup and any flavoring with the gelatin mixture.\n   - In a large bowl, gradually add the powdered sugar to the gelatin mixture, mixing until it starts to come together.\n   - Once it starts forming a dough, knead it by hand until smooth and pliable. You may need to add more powdered sugar or a little water to achieve the desired consistency.\n   - Let the fondant rest, covered with plastic wrap, for a few hours or overnight to improve its elasticity.\n\n#### Poured Fondant:\n1. **Ingredients**:\n   - Granulated sugar\n   - Water\n   - Corn syrup\n   - Flavoring (optional)\n   \n2. **Preparation**:\n   - Combine sugar, water, and corn syrup in a saucepan.\n   - Heat the mixture over medium heat, stirring until the sugar dissolves.\n   - Bring to a boil without stirring, and let it cook until it reaches the soft-ball stage (about 240\u00b0F or 115\u00b0C).\n   - Remove from heat and let it cool slightly before pouring it into a greased pan.\n   - Once it has cooled and thickened, it can be beaten until smooth and creamy.\n\nFondant can be flavored and colored, allowing for a variety of uses in cake decorating. While it\u2019s often used to create a smooth finish on cakes, it can also be molded into shapes or figures for decoration.",
